/vm/ is a place to discuss all types of multiplayer games, whether on console, handheld, or PC, co-op or competitive, online or local.

Does this mean discussion of multiplayer games is banned on other video game boards? No! /vm/ is just a separate board specifically focused on multiplayer games where discussions about your favorite games can thrive.

Please familiarize yourself with the rules and remember to use the spoiler function where appropriate!

Please note that, like /v/, "Generals"—long-term, one-after-the-other, recurring threads about a specific game are not permitted on /vm/. Such threads belong on >>>/vg/

name: Anonymous
com:
SRB2 Kart is a mod of a mod based on the Doom Legacy engine, turning the game engine into a kart racer akin to Super Mario Kart. It's a very lightweight game and runs on most all PCs. Use this thread to start netgames, join other anons, give help/tips, spritework, modding, feedback, etc.

>How to Play (v1.3)
https://github.com/STJr/Kart-Public/releases/tag/v1.3
1. Download the game below in 'Full Install (...)'
>Compiling on Linux
https://wiki.srb2.org/wiki/Source_code_compiling/Makefiles#Compiling_on_Linux
2. Unzip contents into a separate folder
3. Load up 'srb2kart.exe'
4. That's it

>Do we have a /v/ server?!
Yes! We're now running on a new modified EXE that allows for more characters and up to 32 racers. First, download it here:
https://mega.nz/file/ncpRjRYZ#yoVkgXmKNUjdh__jHpmUGgh30J7jlj6RIS8XjbTXKeE (both 32 and 64 bit)

or compile it here:
https://gitlab.com/c3851/srb-2-k-cep
Then, you need to download the add-ons and mods (characters, maps, and racing mods). Get them here:
https://mega.nz/folder/PVgWAB7Y#Fo7sB6yvvek3A9MoSzoCOQ (new addons for updates are in the server anon folder)

[{'no': 775155, 'now': '12/10/22(Sat)04:20:32', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>775147
Thx, I guess I'll do the Azimuth unlock first, do AX/Guardian weapons work on normal targets or is it one loadout for pirates one for thargoids? (or half-half I guess if you want to be able to deal with any situation)', 'time': 1670664032, 'resto': 753572}, {'no': 775158, 'now': '12/10/22(Sat)04:34:10', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>775155
They'll damage human ships but most AX weapons are terrible for it. Pretty much just the traded-for variety of plasma charger is somewhat passable against normal targets because it deals 100% absolute damage, has a high armor piercing rating and a projectile speed of 6KM/sec so it's almost hitscan.
Some handy utility modules are also Guardian unlocks if you haven't already done so, like the FSD booster.
One thing to be careful of with any guardian equipment though, is that in very specific circumstances the goids have overload fields that target guardian technology and will cause those modules specifically to break down and become inoperable until you go repair them.
So far this only happens in HIP 22460 (the entire system), within a few ls of thargoid maelstroms (only present in a few systems, and not really a place you do AX combat anyway), and Orthrus interceptors can nail you with a close-range field.
Orthrus are new recon units only found in Threat 4 nonhuman signal sources inside systems in thargoid alert state. You can't encounter them in AX warzones by accident.', 'time': 1670664850, 'resto': 753572}, {'no': 775159, 'now': '12/10/22(Sat)04:47:56', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>775158
>Guardian unlocks
thought these were for thargoid gameplay only, will have to look into those, thx', 'time': 1670665676, 'resto': 753572}, {'no': 775164, 'now': '12/10/22(Sat)05:08:27', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>775159
The FSD booster is the only general purpose one. There's also defensive modules meant for fighting thargoids that happen to also be useful in other situations.
All guardian defense modules require power to function, which is their main downside.
Guardian hull reinforcement packages provide a better hull boost than baseline human ones, but less than fully engineered. They also provide 5% caustic resistance to help mitigate that kind of damage from goids.
Guardian module reinforcement packages are straight up better than human ones aside from the power requirement. They also reduce how badly thargoid tech makes your ship glitch out.
Guardian shield reinforcement modules have no human equivalent. They just give you a flat +MJ to your shields like HRPs do for hull. Can actually benefit ships with naturally shit shields that don't scale well with percentage-based boosters, like the fedbricks.', 'time': 1670666907, 'resto': 753572}, {'no': 775187, 'now': '12/10/22(Sat)05:56:52', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>FDev broke the fucking mission board

com:
Welcome to /VM/abinogi. Mabinogi is a fun, once popular little old school Korean MMO from 2004 based around Celtic mythology with many different features. Your character can age, rebirth, eat food and gain weight, play and custom make music, and so much more. You can be anything and do anything all at once with no downsides. From non combat related skills like cooking, tailoring, blacksmithing, trading goods in a commerce, carpentry, etc. to different styles of combat like melee, magic, ninja, archery, puppetry, etc. all on 1 character. Although graphics and gameplay is still a bit dated, even after 14 years the game is still rich in content such as fashion contests, cooking contest, jousting, playing in or viewing large concerts, training pets, and so on and continues to be Nexon's most generous game.

>News and Events
https://mabinogi.nexon.net/news/all

>ALL SERVERS HAVE BEEN MERGED
>Many combat talents, life talents, commerce system, field bosses have been revamped
>New Hybrid Talents coming called Arcana talents

>11/17/2022
>Skill training, Renown, Grandmaster, and Crusader skills have become a lot easier to train(lowered training requirements)


>[Guilds]
We currently have a guild called Mabigen. Our guild stone is located by the Taillteann graveyard. Apply by mentioning you're from /vm/.


>[Helpful links - These links contain useful guides and other stuff.]
>Beginners guide and outline to just some of mabinogi's features.
https://docs.google.com/document/d/1of49rjWooRxDJZhrwmiZQRHneXt-ElcuvvzNvPjiZtA/edit#

>wiki for Mabinogi
https://wiki.mabinogiworld.com/view/Wiki_Home

>Skill Training Guild
https://docs.google.com/document/d/1UefjxRzcQWza26VaJapHl77eH429SR2bjkpkkLLggYw/edit#

>Best In Slot Gear guide and gear progression
https://docs.google.com/document/d/1sq3Sa0AaOuQ087rb2CR5fBK9F4gE2Uz6LjsdBgWtscQ/edit#heading=h.kt0ezt1btzid

>Mabinogi Guide to Guides
https://docs.google.com/document/d/1oXG_vtjkVxWWxez9u8yINlVkEUezl7RnvymKnoCbfNU/edit#

name: /bng/ - BallisticNG Saturday races
com:
>What is this game?
BallisticNG is a PC anti-gravity racing game available on Steam for $8, based mostly on Wip3out, with optional mechanics from the newer Wipeout games.
If you like going fast, good tunes, and good fun, this game is for you.

>How do I join?
Get the game (Grab the Outer Reaches DLC for $3 if you want, though not required as we mostly play custom tracks anyway).
Download and install the track pack (instructions in the pastebin).
Launch the game, go to Multiplayer, and join what is most likely the only public Steam lobby online. If we are playing in an IP lobby (piratefag friendly) it will be designated at the end of this post or within the thread.

Everything else you need will be here:
https://pastebin.com/tHrNfZdv
Make sure you get the Trackpack
Newest Trackpack (last updated: 2022/09/22):
https://mega.nz/file/m4gHVJQJ#_ay4DAvFLsQ4hlHzDrsZp_9uGjyyVQucGb4HSSdTA_I
Newest Minipack, get this if you're just updating your track pack:
https://mega.nz/file/el4jFCzT#-0lH7G1ENVLM-9lfUE4a11DAwksbw2xPEvzhDfWd6yo
See pastebin for instructions on how to install or update your pack without causing the game to fail to recognize which tracks you have installed.

>How do I play?
Anon guide will be posted, there's 3 parts covering most basics.
Try to practice airbraking and things for a little bit using the Campaign's practice mode before jumping right in otherwise you'll probably have a hard time.
We can also answer any questions you might have, either here or within the lobby.

>I'm bad and not going to win!
Once you get above the skill floor anyone can win races due to their chaotic nature.
Also we always get newfriends who will match your skill level.

We also have a steam group: https://steamcommunity.com/groups/ballisticnv
This is used just for organizing race sessions, no circlejerking.

com:
Another Friday night another chance to play BGO with /v/. Never played before? Just hop in the link bellow (google and /v/ archive it if you don't trust, has been a dying /v/ tradition for decades) with no registration needed as you can play as a guest and chat. What is this? This is a turned based mario party style game where the goal is to fuck eachother over and cross the finish line yourself to win. Most items and skills can be used on anyones turn like throwing a grenade at someone visiting a shop or are put in an event que for your turn so there's many levels of thinking to get ahead. This game is full of relic memes from 2010 with new stuff constantly added as the game aged with whacky stuff like being able to rape other players, hypnotize others into becoming vegans who die if they eat meat, lighting players on fire and burning all their pets alive, or turning into pacman and eating everyone for points.

These games may take a while to fill and run a while depending on the end space and player count. Be sure to get things like food ready as if you go AFK during your turn too long you may be kicked from the game by other irritated players. We are hosting in a private lobby and anyone can make their own game for this thread, even without an account. An anchor post will be bellow where the first game will be posted and where players can check replies to jump to the most recent game being hosted without having to scroll down the thread.

com:
Are you an elder Millennial or Gen Xer who has fond memories of the greatest MMO ever made? Did you know that there is a thriving AC emu community with multiple servers? Well, there is and the latest addition to the emu server stable is the best one yet. Dekarutide is a reimagining of classic (pre-Throne of Destiny) AC that makes the game far more challenging and - in many players' opinions - fun.
>Daily patches & updates by Dekaru himself, he has worked on this project for years before finally releasing it to the public.
>Lootgen gems are infinite use, cast buffs on you & can be replenished with mana charges
>Jewelry can now have attributes on it
>Many older quest rewards made relevant
>No cottages/villas/mansions, just apartments and theyre all linked together
>12 pack slots in apts
>No item/creature magic
>No weeping/hollow/etc, you can find lootgen slayers and other properties from mobs and vendors
>New skills
>Skill and Damage formulae completely redone
>New Ley Line Amulets - you buy Life and War Magic amulets from an archmage and find a Menhir ring (stone formation) in dereth (there's 10-20 of them) and you can meditate in the Menhir ring formation and imbue the amulet with a random property that passively buffs your character with either increased damage or increased effect of some sort of skill. These amulets are attuned/bonded and fit in the cloak slot
>New aiming system
>Aim high: Chance of doing more damage
>Aim medium: Chance of target evasion lowered
>Aim low: Chance of you evading target increased

name: Anonymous
sub: /LFG/ - Small MMORPG looking for group general
com:
Do you play an MMORPG (or private server) that is generally too small to level with other people either because everyone else is at level cap, group leveling is considered outdated, or because there is just not enough people to form groups for group content? Is there an MMORPG or private server that you would play if there were people to level with? Or maybe you're looking for a new MMORPG (or private server) to play with some people.

This is not a thread to find people to play popular MMORPGs with (Guild Wars 2, World of Warcraft or its more popular private servers, New World, Lost Ark, FFXIV, CoH Homecoming, Return of Reckoning, etc). This is for the dead, dying, or just very small MMORPGs (or at least the ones in which it is a struggle or impossible to find people for group content while leveling) such as EverQuest I and II, LotRO, DDO, Asheron's Call, Age of Conan, and small private servers. As ultimately I do not know which ones exactly are hard to find groups for, this is up to your discretion and is ultimately a thread guideline.

Only advertise here if you are serious about helping form a leveling group or even a community (such as a guild) on your game. Coordinate with people on times (if a group) or simply a server and faction/realm (if a guild/community).

You really don't play a lot of MMOs do you?', 'time': 1670554287, 'resto': 746154}, {'no': 774215, 'now': '12/08/22(Thu)22:35:25', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>774200
I do, I just don't play chink button mashers', 'time': 1670556925, 'resto': 746154}, {'no': 774313, 'now': '12/09/22(Fri)01:45:13', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>774135
I'm playing Naraka Bladepoint (melee fighting game BR). Compared to LoL, it has much less of an issue with about the RNG of matchups, because 80% of the game is skill and most fights feel like the better player won. Also, the game is less "class-based" than MMOs because 50% of the combat is the same non-hero/class -based melee mechanics. Simple heroes has made it possible to balance the game in a way where characters don't incredibly hard counter each other. However, in MMOs, there are so many skills that it's impossible to balance it in a way where everyone has fair chance by playing in their unique playstyle.

The flipside of skill-based gameplay is that then your build, actions and plans matter less, which could be a problem in MMO. I would imagine the goal of an MMO is to have that kind of power fantasy of being able to prepare for challenges in your own way.

I haven't played a proper MMO so I don't know how skill-based gameplay fits in MMOs, or what PvP in an MMO even is for, other than abusing power for some sort of profit or sadism, which is both good and bad. Souls PvP has some skill but also matchups, for me the ultimate motivation is making a build that counters my most hated build. While it's just exchanging advantage to another disadvantage, I think this can feel meaningful, and you can definitely balance a game so that one thing is not best against everything.

The truth is that you simply can't have control and power when it's against other players. It's either more about matchups, more about skill, or RNG and circumstances. When you play chess, you have "control" over your actions, but you still don't have control over mistakes you make and thoughts you didn't think. Somebody always loses in PvP. You can only get consistent power fantasy of winning in PvE that's designed to be won, and that's mental masturbation then.', 'time': 1670568313, 'resto': 746154}, {'no': 774421, 'now': '12/09/22(Fri)07:31:17', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>774198

[{'no': 774150, 'now': '12/08/22(Thu)20:06:31', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>773997
Its two part I think. One part is certainly game design and they have designed games to be more accessible at the cost of "requiring" social interaction. On the other hand, players don't like to put in the effort or deal with those requirements to begin with. That's not to say that nobody likes these type of games. FF11 has about 94,000 active users with a yearly revenue of 15-20 million. However, that's not a ton. That's enough to keep it running an a small bit of new content. However, its sister game ff14 made something like 400 million. FF11 also died and one of the major reasons I've seen people mention is difficulty/accessibilty of getting into it.

Lets not also forget that WoW, the biggest MMO of all time, attributed its success to lowering the barriers of entry into the genre (compared to games at the time like EQ). Making it more accessible/casual.

Then you also have a bundle of other MMOs that have gone under where people debate a variety of reasons as to why, and a few of those are that it was too hard.

To me, developers just followed the trend they saw with WoW, and to fairly good success. Sure we complain about it online, but they were financial successes. They basically said "Hey, we're not gonna force group content onto you until you get to endgame. But we will give you the opportunity to connect with others IF you both put in some form of effort". And guess what? Nobody really puts in the effort. So I think its one part the industry has been made hyper accessible and the other part is that the audience, the one that is big enough to keep MMORPGs alive and developing new content, doesn't put in the effort to connect with others. Nevermind the sheer number of people in these games that have the social skills of a pile of shit. Which adds onto why they don't put in the effort.', 'time': 1670547991, 'resto': 765033}, {'no': 774218, 'now': '12/08/22(Thu)22:42:59', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>774150
>the other part is that the audience, the one that is big enough to keep MMORPGs alive and developing new content, doesn't put in the effort to connect with others.
Why are huge swathes of people playing a massively multiplayer online game if they don't want to socialize? Why are they playing MMOs over singleplayer games? Is it because of the dearth of high production value RPGs? (The last ones being Witcher 3 in 2015 and Kingdoms of Amalur in 2012)', 'time': 1670557379, 'resto': 765033}, {'no': 774253, 'now': '12/08/22(Thu)23:20:00', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>774218
So they can buy cosmetics on the cash shop and AFK in cities to show it off.', 'time': 1670559600, 'resto': 765033}, {'no': 774301, 'now': '12/09/22(Fri)01:02:12', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>774218
There's a few reasons. One is that communities are formed outside of games. No longer in them. So they're not putting in effort to meet people in the game because they already are in a community where they socialize on things like discord across multiple games. Another rendition of this is that they're in a parasocial community like a twitch streamer community. So to them, that's who they talk to. Not people in game. The final reason is that many people basically want a singleplayer RPG experience, but they want to be in a world that is shared with players. As players are not NPCs. To these players they're like a hyper advance NPC. They don't interact with them, but they throw in a bit of a wildcard into the mix in which you never know what they're gonna do or how they behave. As the other anon said, it also helps that they can show off their accomplishments.

You can still find groups via going on guild recruitment sites for various games and looking for a guild that fits your personality. But even then you gotta put in the effort to routinely interact with the guild to get "into" the group and be included beyond just a group. But even then, most of your socialization will be happening over things like discord. Not with randoms in game. But even then, a wide portion of players will only join guilds for easy groups and wont engage any further because of the above reasons. I used to run a guild in a major MMORPG that had I think 500 members. Beyond group events, we'd normally have 10-20 players in discord during peak hours. Even though at any one time you'd have 100-150 players online. And it was usually the same 10-20 people. The remaining players wouldn't talk in chat. Wouldn't engage. They show up for raids, guild events, whatever. But wouldn't talk. They do the content, then go off do their own thing.', 'time': 1670565732, 'resto': 765033}, {'no': 774332, 'now': '12/09/22(Fri)02:36:29', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>772747
>imagine that if a good mmorpg were released today and it did everything right, you would be playing it
Well of course but that won't happen, it's unrealistic. People are burned out on MMOs because the future for them looks so bleak and as mediocre as it has been for the past decade. When devs can't get shit right for 10+ years and don't even engage with the different parts of their community enough to try and figure out what each of them like it gets demoralizing.

The fact that wow and ffxiv are still such giants and that absolutely nothing has ever been able to compare is demoralizing. MMORPG players have seen game after game die to various reasons. P2W and greed, incompetence or simply not giving a fuck. Archeage for instance is one of them with the most potential anyone had seen in an MMO, it died literally because the devs were greedy and it's such a stupid fucking reason.

It's pretty much expected nowadays that when a new MMO releases it's either going to be a tedious cashgrab with mechanics specifically designed to inconvenience players and pressure them into paying for something that would solve the dogshit predatory mechanic, or that it's going to die within a year or two because the devs didn't address certain issues or made poor decisions in design while in development hell.', 'time': 1670571389, 'resto': 765033}]

There are a lot of things to despise about Diablo Immortal, but they have nailed it in terms of community. For a while I suspected that my good experience was the result of choosing a server called Deckard Cain - perhaps an older player base eager to represent for D2 - but after a merge with three other servers I was proven wrong. Immortal has the best community I've seen since the early days of Minecraft. It's deliberate and revolutionary, and I'm afraid we will lose it when the game fails, just as we lost countless good ideas when Asheron's Call and Anarchy Online failed.

To try and keep this as simple as possible:

The guilds on an Immoral server do some challenges to become Shadow, which is a sort of brotherhood of guilds who are in a constant cycle to overthrow the Immortals, a set of 3 allied guilds with special privileges. Each week, the Shadow guilds work to increase their power, then compete against each other for the right to challenge the Immortal guilds. The top ranking Shadows then fight the Immortals, and if they win a throwdown ensues to determine which Shadow guild will take the Immortal throne. When they do this, they pick two other guilds to join them.

What all this boils down to is regular competition between guilds who mostly need to work together, towards a showdown between factions whose members used to be allies and will be allies again soon. In half a year of playing, I have NEVER seen toxicity in chat beyond a short burst of infighting following the server merge. I am a terrible player with a gimped character, but I'm in one of the top guilds on my server, and have a raiding group that carries me. Before and after any contest you see nothing but gg and thanks in the public chat. >Installation Guides:
Image guide: https://imgur.com/a/G2fK1Z0
Registration: https://p.eagate.573.jp/gate/k/newcomer.html
Download: https://p.eagate.573.jp/game/eacbg/bg/download/installer.html
Private Server: https://files.catbox.moe/che7wb.zip (Download and swap out your modules folder and you can queue with /v/. Remember to back up your previous module.)

>Technical errors:
If you can't get past the bench test screen, change your computer's region to Japanese in the control panel
If your NAT type is below C, try forwarding port 5291 on your router.
If you encounter error 1012, download the newest Microsoft update or rollback to your previous Windows update.


>Wtf is the point of my role?:
Bombers destroy buildings and dig for items.
Attackers make space by separating enemies either by distracting or killing them.
Shooters make it to mid as soon as possible for the first team fights before going back to base to defend.
Blockers delay any inevitable attacks for as long as possible by denying area and stalling with heals, buffs, and blocks.

All characters have i-frames on their ults. Attackers will have i-frames on any of their skills that will do damage.
This means something like Oren's riceball will not have i-frames.

com:
>>How to connect
From wii.guide/wiimmfi:
>Wii (no homebrew)
1. Insert your game disc.
2. Go into your internet connection settings and set the DNS server of your console to 95.217.77.151.
3. Go to the WC24 contract information (third button after clicking on “Internet” in the settings).
4. Confirm that you do want to use WC24 and the shop channel
5. The Wiimmfi patcher page should show up. If it doesn’t, and you still see the default license agreement, your router might not be compatible with this method.
6. Wait for about 1 minute and 30 seconds for the patcher to load
The game should now start with the Wiimmfi patch included
>Nintendo DS
You'll need a Wi-Fi network with WEP or no security
1. Go in the Nintendo DS Wi-Fi settings. This can be accessed inside the game you want to play online with.
2. Set up a connection.
3. Type in 164.132.44.106 as the primary DNS.
4. Type in 1.1.1.1 as the secondary DNS (if it gives you problems, try 8.8.8.8).
5. Save your connection settings and perform a connection test. If it’s successful, then you’re ready to play.
>Supported games
https://wiimmfi.de/stat?m=6e
